  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Edict to Minister Lim Won-hou Refusing His Second Request for Resignation
  author: Choe Yu-cheong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    An edict to Lim Won-hou:

    I have reviewed your second memorial requesting release from office and recommending a successor. Know that the stability of the realm rests upon the prime minister as surely as human movement depends upon limbs and joints. Without true accord between ruler and minister, how could governance flourish without effort, as if by nature's own hand?

    You possess a generous spirit and penetrating wisdom. Your lineage joins both noble birth and imperial kinship. Your position commands the weightiest office of state. Through your steady hand, the realm's shortcomings are mended and my heart finds satisfaction. Through Confucian learning, you lend counsel to the state's governance. Your merit is abundant, and your reward must be substantial. Therefore, following the proper succession of ranks, I have appointed you to this crucial responsibility.

    Promotion follows its natural order; appointment stems from merit, not favoritism. Yet why do you plead insufficiency and defer to those of equal standing? Though ancient records tell of Han Hu yielding power to Ziwu, such precedents do not alter commands once given. And did Bayi's reticence ever overturn the heavenly mandate?

    Abide no longer in false modesty. Let your service accord with the trust I place in you.
  footnotes:
    - Han Hu (罕虎) and Ziwu (子產) were ancient sage-rulers known for their virtuous governance; the reference suggests legendary models of political wisdom.
    - Bayi (伯益) and Xiong Bi (熊羆) refer to legendary figures whose attempted abdication was never sanctioned, emphasizing that celestial mandate cannot be refused.
    - The edict employs classical analogies to persuade Won-hou that declining office contradicts both cosmic order and the sovereign's will.
